## Security Review: `app.js`

The application is a minimal Express.js server (20 lines of code), so there are no active exploits like SQL injection or XSS present — but the code establishes several dangerous patterns that will become real vulnerabilities as the app grows. Below are the findings, ranked by severity.

---

### 🔴 Critical

#### 1. No Authentication or Authorization on `/users` (OWASP A01 – Broken Access Control)

The `/users` endpoint is completely public and returns user PII (names + email addresses) with zero access control. Any unauthenticated request gets the full user list.

```js
// ❌ Current — wide open
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([...]);
});

// ✅ Fix — require a valid JWT (or session) first
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function authenticate(req, res, next) {
  const token = req.headers['authorization']?.split(' ')[1];
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });

  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET);
    next();
  } catch {
    res.status(403).json({ error: 'Forbidden' });
  }
}

app.get('/users', authenticate, (req, res) => { ... });
```

---

### 🔴 Critical

#### 2. Missing Security Headers (OWASP A05 – Security Misconfiguration)

Express sends no hardening headers by default. Without them, browsers allow clickjacking, MIME sniffing, and other client-side attacks.

```js
// ✅ Fix — add helmet (sets ~14 headers in one line)
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
// Adds: X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, HSTS,
//       Content-Security-Policy, Referrer-Policy, etc.
```

---

### 🟠 High

#### 3. No Rate Limiting (OWASP A04 – Insecure Design)

There is no throttling on any route. This exposes the server to brute-force attacks and denial-of-service.

```js
// ✅ Fix — apply a rate limiter globally
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // 100 requests per window per IP
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
});

app.use(limiter);
```

---

### 🟠 High

#### 4. No CORS Policy

Without an explicit CORS configuration, Express allows all cross-origin requests in some deployment scenarios. This should be locked down explicitly.

```js
// ✅ Fix — restrict to known origins
const cors = require('cors');

app.use(cors({
  origin: ['https://your-frontend.example.com'],
  methods: ['GET', 'POST'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Content-Type', 'Authorization'],
}));
```

