### 🟠 HIGH — A04: Insecure Design — No Rate Limiting

There is no rate limiting on any endpoint. An attacker can hammer `/users` (or any future auth endpoint) indefinitely — enabling credential stuffing, enumeration, or denial-of-service.

**Fix:** Use [`express-rate-limit`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/express-rate-limit):

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // max 100 requests per window per IP
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
  message: { error: 'Too many requests, please try again later.' },
});

app.use(limiter); // apply globally, or per-route for sensitive endpoints
```

---

### 🟠 HIGH — A02: Cryptographic Failures — No HTTPS Enforcement

The server listens on plain HTTP port 3000 with no TLS and no redirect to HTTPS. Any data in transit (including auth tokens, user PII) is transmitted in cleartext.

**Fix:** In production, terminate TLS at a reverse proxy (nginx, AWS ALB, etc.) and enforce redirects. In Node directly:

```js
// Redirect HTTP → HTTPS at the app layer (behind a proxy)
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  if (req.headers['x-forwarded-proto'] !== 'https' && process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production') {
    return res.redirect(301, `https://${req.headers.host}${req.url}`);
  }
  next();
});

// Trust the proxy so req.ip and x-forwarded-proto work correctly
app.set('trust proxy', 1);
```

